<HEADLINE>
<P>
JULIA DAVIS STUART; LED LEAGUE OF WOMEN VOTERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Julia Davis Stuart, 79, president of the League of Women Voters of the United 
States from 1964 to 1968 and the first Westerner to hold that office. During 
her tenure as national president, Mrs. Stuart was noted for extensive work in 
conservation of water resources. 
</P>
<P>
In 1969, she was honored on the 50th anniversary of the league by President 
Richard M. Nixon at a White House ceremony. Mrs. Stuart also served on 
President Lyndon B. Johnson's 19-member Commission of Law Enforcement and 
Administration of Justice and on the National Citizens Commission on 
International Cooperation. She was president of the Spokane, Wash., chapter of 
the League of Women Voters from 1951 to 1953. She later served four years as 
the league's Washington state president. In 1960, she was elected to the 
national board and two years later became national second vice president. In 
Spokane on Saturday of unreported causes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
