<HEADLINE>
<P>
OCCIDENTAL; 
</P>
<P>
VETERAN TEAM LOOKS LIKE A TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GARY KLEIN, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They are teams of similar experience and, Coach Jeff Henderson hopes, similar 
destiny. 
</P>
<P>
The Occidental College baseball team begins the 1990 season Saturday at 
Westmont with more veteran players than any Tiger club since 1982 -- the year 
Occidental won its last Southern California Intercollegiate Athletic Conference 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
Henderson, in his fifth season as Occidental's coach, was a second baseman for 
the 1982 champions. 
</P>
<P>
"We had a lot of four-year starters that year and this year we do too," 
Henderson said. "There's a camaraderie that develops with a group like that. 
They've been together a long time working hard toward a goal. 
</P>
<P>
"The SCIAC title is a realistic goal for us this year." 
</P>
<P>
The Tigers have every player back from a team that finished 22-17 overall and 
10-8 in the SCIAC last season. Among them are pitcher Dave Stoll and infielder 
Tom Bonetto, both of whom were selected first team all-conference. 
</P>
<P>
Stoll, a 5-foot-11, 175-pound sophomore left-hander, was 8-3 with a 3.39 
earned-run average as a freshman and led the conference with 82 strikeouts in 
85 innings. 
</P>
<P>
Bonetto, a senior who is a four-year starter, led the conference in batting 
last season with a .434 average and was selected second-team All-American. This 
season, he moves from second base to third to make way for junior Mark Dalton 
(.207) 
</P>
<P>
Other veterans include junior shortstop Mark Harris (.370), sophomore first 
baseman Mike Bonetto (.354 and a conference-leading 10 home runs) and senior 
catcher Mike Knisely (.314). All three players were second-team all-conference 
selections in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
"One of our goals in the off-season was to strengthen the pitching staff 
through recruiting," Henderson said, "and I think we were successful." 
</P>
<P>
Rich Mather, a freshman right-hander from Corona del Mar, and junior 
right-hander Mark Teitelman, a transfer from Johns Hopkins, are expected to 
have the greatest impact. They join senior right-handers Rob Drew and Isidro 
Rodriguez and junior right-hander Jason Rusk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
