<HEADLINE>
<P>
AFTER 20 YEARS, WOMAN SQUATTER FACES EVICTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DERBY, Conn. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A judge on Wednesday ordered the eviction of a 72-year-old woman who has been 
living for nearly 20 years in a ramshackle homestead on the proposed site of a 
state park. 
</P>
<P>
Doris Gagnon was granted an automatic 20-day stay, and Superior Court Judge 
Karen Sequino said it is likely the woman will be found eligible for a stay of 
up to nine months. 
</P>
<P>
During a hearing Tuesday, Gagnon said she preferred to live with dozens of 
animals at her makeshift home on state property than move to senior citizen 
housing. 
</P>
<P>
Gagnon has been fighting the state since the mid-1960s, when efforts began to 
establish a park on the 200-acre site along Long Island Sound. Her cottage was 
demolished in 1971, but she refused to leave the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020190-0133 </DOCNO>
