WORLD IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
CZECHOSLOVAKIA; 
</P>
<P>
LAST OF OLD GUARD COMMUNISTS QUITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Frantisek Pitra, the last old guard Communist left in power by Czechoslovakia's 
peaceful revolution, resigned as leader of the Czech republic, the official 
news agency CTK reported. 
</P>
<P>
Pitra, 57, is also expected to give up his job as deputy prime minister. CTK 
did not give the reason for Pitra's resignation, which came a day after the 
Communists ended 40 years of dominance in Parliament by giving more than 100 of 
their seats to pro-democracy groups. The realignment completed an effort to 
include those groups in Parliament before June 8 elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
