1354 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HILL ELUDES FALLOUT IN FBI INQUIRY; 
</P>
<P>
POLITICS: NO CHARGES HAVE BEEN FILED AGAINST THE WHITTIER ASSEMBLYMAN. HIS 
CAPITOL CLOUT IS UNCHANGED. AND HE'S RAKING IN ENDORSEMENTS IN HIS RACE FOR A 
STATE SENATE SEAT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVE LESHER, TIMES POLITICAL WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Seventeen months ago, FBI agents raided the offices of Assemblyman Frank Hill, 
then one of the most promising Republicans in the state Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
It appeared that the FBI investigation into alleged influence peddling in 
Sacramento put Hill's career in jeopardy. But today, more than a year later, 
there are still no charges against Hill. And instead of waiting for 
investigators to resolve the cloud over his future, the 36-year-old legislator 
has decided to trust his fate to the voters in an election Tuesday to replace 
former state Sen. William Campbell. 
</P>
<P>
The FBI probe "is something I can't control, so I've just got to go on with my 
life," Hill said in a recent interview. "I didn't do anything wrong (and) I 
would like to keep trying to move up." 
</P>
<P>
Hill of Whittier was the first candidate to launch a bid for Campbell's 31st 
District seat, announcing his candidacy just hours after the veteran legislator 
from Hacienda Heights resigned last October to take a job in the private 
sector. 
</P>
<P>
He is facing seven contenders for the job, three of them from the San Gabriel 
Valley: Diamond Bar City Councilman Gary G. Miller, a Republican; West Covina 
Councilman Bradley J. McFadden, a Democrat; and Rowland Heights resident Robert 
W. Lewis, the American Independent Party candidate. The 31st senate district 
includes portions of Covina, Diamond Bar, Hacienda Heights, Industry, Rowland 
Heights, Valinda, Walnut, and West Covina. 
</P>
<P>
If none of the candidates receives more than 50% of the vote Tuesday, the top 
vote-getters from each party will enter an April 10 runoff. 
</P>
<P>
During the Senate campaign, the FBI investigation has kept Hill's name in the 
newspapers, and his opponents in the race have made it a campaign issue. 
</P>
<P>
But the investigation does not appear to have had a significant effect on 
Hill's clout in the Capitol or, so far, on his bid for higher office. 
</P>
<P>
Republicans don't often choose sides in a contested primary, but in this race 
that includes four Republicans, Hill has been endorsed by at least 18 
legislators. That's more than either of the two Republican state senators 
running for lieutenant governor. 
</P>
<P>
"For those of us who felt free to endorse him, we are embracing the idea that 
he's innocent until proven guilty," said Ken Maddy of Fresno, the Senate 
minority leader. "I think he has the respect of everyone up here. Putting aside 
this FBI thing, I don't think there's any doubt that if most of us had to pick 
the top five Assembly members, he'd be one of them." 
</P>
<P>
Hill has also proven to be a strong fund-raiser. In finance statements filed 
last week, Hill reported almost $300,000 raised since the Senate race started 
Dec. 24, almost seven times that of one of his three GOP opponents, Assemblyman 
Gil Ferguson (R-Newport Beach), who raised the second-highest amount with about 
$44,000. 
</P>
<P>
The two other Republicans in the race, Ron Isles and Miller, are independently 
wealthy and have financed their races out of their own pockets. Isles, a Brea 
city councilman, reported a campaign funds of $189,000, but $175,000 of it was 
his own money. Miller, the city councilman from Diamond Bar, had $273,500, 
including a $270,000 loan to himself. 
</P>
<P>
Legislators, lobbyists and Capitol staffers say the FBI probe has not 
diminished Hill's influence and effectiveness. He is still a member of the 
elite inner circle of only four Republicans who meet regularly with the 
governor to plan strategy and legislation. 
</P>
<P>
"I haven't seen any change," said Assemblyman Richard E. Floyd (D-Carson), 
chairman of the Government Operations Committee on which Hill is ranking 
Republican. "There's a matter of respect and, my goodness, it's just one of 
those things." 
</P>
<P>
The FBI investigation has reportedly focused on a payment Hill received in a 
meeting June 27, 1988, from officials representing Peachstate Capital West Ltd. 
The officials turned out to be undercover FBI agents and Peachstate was an FBI 
front. 
</P>
<P>
In testimony during the trial of state Sen. Joseph B. Montoya (D-Whittier), the 
only legislator charged so far in the scandal, one prosecution witness said he 
arranged for a $5,000 payment to Hill in return for his support on a bill 
sponsored by Peachstate. 
</P>
<P>
Two months after the June meeting, FBI agents searched the offices of four 
legislators, including Hill's, capping a three-year undercover sting operation. 
</P>
<P>
The FBI investigation has rocked Sacramento so much that polls now show most 
people believe legislators take bribes. And the scandal has become ammunition 
for anti-incumbency campaigns against some of those who weren't even involved. 
</P>
<P>
Some of Hill's opponents in the Senate race are using the scandal as an issue 
against Hill, including one candidate, Lewis of Rowland Heights, who has formed 
a committee called "Throw the Rascals Out." Nevertheless, some Capitol 
observers say they believe Hill is the front-runner in the race, based on his 
power base and fund-raising abilities. 
</P>
<P>
The race, however, is difficult to handicap because voter turnout is expected 
to be extremely low. That means a strong showing by one faction of voters -- 
pro-choice supporters, for example -- could make a significant difference in 
the outcome. The race is also largely invisible because the candidates are 
relying mostly on direct mail campaign rather than media advertisements. 
</P>
<P>
The 31st District is split almost in half by the border between Los Angeles and 
Orange counties. It stretches from West Covina and Whittier in the north to 
Laguna Beach in the south. It is also overwhelmingly Republican, by a 54% to 
36% margin. 
</P>
<P>
To some colleagues, Hill's decision to run for Campbell's seat was not a 
question of whether he should seek higher office, but whether he was going to 
continue in the Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
"He had a choice of either running for what was a logical step up at a time 
when he would be expected to move up, or quit (politics) because he would face 
the same thing if he tried to run again for the Assembly," Maddy said. "I think 
he did what he had to do." 
</P>
<P>
Those who know Hill were not surprised that he would run. A hunter and 
outdoorsman who was elected to the Legislature at 28, Hill has always been 
known for a brazen if not cocky attitude. Critics call it arrogance. 
</P>
<P>
Critics and supporters, however, attribute Hill's success to two dominant 
character traits: a sense of humor and a no-nonsense reputation for knowing how 
and when to play hardball. 
</P>
<P>
"I've never been one to sugar-coat things," Hill said. "So if you don't go 
along, you shouldn't be surprised if you don't keep that committee assignment." 
</P>
<P>
City Council members in Diamond Bar, which is part of Hill's Assembly district, 
recently learned the consequences of crossing swords with the assemblyman. 
</P>
<P>
They wanted legislation last month to resolve a minor, but potentially 
expensive technical mistake in the charter for the new city. Hill told The 
Times, however, that he would only carry the measure if Miller, the Republican 
councilman, promised not to challenge him in the Senate race. 
</P>
<P>
Outraged, Miller entered the race and the Diamond Bar city attorney referred 
the issue to the Los Angeles County district attorney's office, where it is 
still being reviewed, according to Miller. Hill now denies making the remark. 
</P>
<P>
Hill has also been involved in controversy for accepting sizable honorariums or 
contributions and then voting on issues that benefit the contributors. 
</P>
<P>
Assemblyman Stan Statham (R-Oak Run), a Hill supporter, said one of the main 
reasons Hill is so effective at the Capitol is his sense of humor. 
</P>
<P>
"In this world where we all take ourselves too seriously, an asset like Frank 
Hill is in short supply," Statham said. "Politics often comes down to a 
personality contest. . . . When you choose between two good sides, you often go 
with your friend." 
</P>
<P>
Statham added, however, that the campaign for Campbell's seat is being watched 
closely to see how voters will respond to the FBI investigation. 
</P>
<P>
"This race will be a good example of how the investigation and negative 
campaigning will work," he said. "Here it is a year later and it's like it 
never happened. . . . Will another shoe drop? Only the FBI knows." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Frank Hill 
</P>
