<P>
HEIR GETS PRISON FOR MOLESTATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
HENDERSONVILLE, N.C. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The heir to a textile fortune was sentenced today to 150 days in prison and 
five years probation for molesting two youngsters at a Blue Ridge Mountains 
summer camp for rich kids. 
</P>
<P>
John Yorke Pharr III, grandson of a founder of Stowe-Pharr textile mills, was 
sentenced to five years in prison, suspended on the condition that he serve 150 
days in state prison followed by five years of supervised probation. 
</P>
<P>
Pharr, 41, continued to insist he is innocent of charges that he took indecent 
liberties with minors attending Camp Falling Creek, a summer camp for 
privileged children that Pharr owned in Tuxedo, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
Four children testified against Pharr during his trial, each telling nearly 
identical accounts of being taken on skinny dipping outings and then invited to 
share his sleeping bag, during which they said the molestations occurred. 
</P>
<P>
Pharr said he shared his sleeping bag with the youngsters, who were each 10 
years old, because they were homesick. 
</P>
</TEXT>
