<P>
$422,000 TO INJURED STUNT MAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A High Court judge awarded $422,000 in damages to a stunt man who claimed his 
career was ended by injuries caused in a fall during the filming of the movie 
"Superman IV." 
</P>
<P>
London Cannon Films Ltd. admitted liability. But John Lees, 47, said the award 
does not make up for the injuries he suffered when harness wires snapped and he 
fell 25 feet. 
</P>
<P>
"My career as a stunt man is over," said Lees, whose heels and left ankle were 
broken. He was unable under British law to specify to the court how much he 
wanted in damages. His lawyer told the court that Lees has undergone surgery 
and physiotherapy but is permanently disabled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
