<HEADLINE>
<P>
NAMES IN THE NEWS; 
</P>
<P>
'MATLOCK' HATED THE LAUGHTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Andy Griffith credits a grammar school performance and his hatred of being 
laughed at as the impetus for his acting career. 
</P>
<P>
"I was laughed at all the time" as a child, the 63-year-old actor said in an 
interview in Parade magazine for next Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
He recalled an instance during a third-grade play that made him realize that he 
could make people laugh with him, instead of at him. 
</P>
<P>
"I discovered that I could control why they laughed by doing something overt to 
make them laugh," Griffith said. "I was being laughed at, I hated it, so I made 
an adjustment to control the situation. All comics learn that." 
</P>
<P>
The result was a successful career that included eight years as Mayberry's 
lovable sheriff on "The Andy Griffith Show," a host of specials and most 
recently "Matlock," a series in which he plays a lawyer who always gets his 
clients off the hook. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
